phase1.code:
public class WrapperExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Wrapper classes provide object representation of primitives
        // Primitive → Wrapper: Integer, Double, Boolean, Character, etc.

        // 1. Autoboxing — automatically converts primitive to wrapper
        System.out.println("=== Autoboxing ===");
        Integer intObj = 42;  // int → Integer (automatic)
        Double doubleObj = 3.14;  // double → Double
        Boolean boolObj = true;   // boolean → Boolean
        Character charObj = 'A';  // char → Character

        System.out.println("Integer: " + intObj);
        System.out.println("Double: " + doubleObj);
        System.out.println("Boolean: " + boolObj);
        System.out.println("Character: " + charObj);

        // 2. Unboxing — automatically converts wrapper to primitive
        System.out.println("=== Unboxing ===");
        int intValue = intObj;  // Integer → int (automatic)
        double doubleValue = doubleObj;  // Double → double
        boolean boolValue = boolObj;  // Boolean → boolean

        System.out.println("intValue: " + intValue);
        System.out.println("doubleValue: " + doubleValue);

        // 3. Useful wrapper methods
        System.out.println("=== Utility Methods ===");

        // Parsing strings to numbers
        int parsedInt = Integer.parseInt("123");
        double parsedDouble = Double.parseDouble("45.67");
        System.out.println("Parsed int: " + parsedInt);
        System.out.println("Parsed double: " + parsedDouble);

        // Converting int to String
        String intStr = Integer.toString(456);
        System.out.println("String: " + intStr);

        // Wrapper constants
        System.out.println("Integer max: " + Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        System.out.println("Integer min: " + Integer.MIN_VALUE);
        System.out.println("Double max: " + Double.MAX_VALUE);

        // 4. Collections use wrappers (can't use primitives)
        System.out.println("=== Collections ===");
        java.util.ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new java.util.ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(10);   // Autoboxing: int → Integer
        numbers.add(20);
        numbers.add(30);

        for (int num : numbers) {  // Unboxing: Integer → int
            System.out.println(num);
        }

        // 5. null is possible with wrappers (danger!)
        System.out.println("=== null danger ===");
        Integer nullable = null;
        // int x = nullable;  // NullPointerException!
        System.out.println("Can be null: " + nullable);
    }
}

phase2.brokenCode:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Integer x = null;

        // Unboxing a null reference
        int y = x;  // NullPointerException!

        System.out.println(y);
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
When you unbox a null wrapper, Java tries to call intValue() on a null reference.

This causes a NullPointerException at runtime.

Always check for null before unboxing:

if (x != null) {
    int y = x;  // Safe
} else {
    System.out.println("x is null!");
}

This is a common gotcha when using wrappers!

phase3.solution:
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Autoboxing
        Integer intObj = 42;
        Double doubleObj = 3.14;
        Boolean boolObj = true;

        System.out.println("Integer: " + intObj);
        System.out.println("Double: " + doubleObj);
        System.out.println("Boolean: " + boolObj);

        // 2. parseInt
        int num = Integer.parseInt("999");
        System.out.println("Parsed: " + num);

        // 3. Constants
        System.out.println("Max: " + Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        System.out.println("Min: " + Integer.MIN_VALUE);

        // 4-5. ArrayList with autoboxing/unboxing
        ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(10);
        numbers.add(20);
        numbers.add(30);
        numbers.add(40);
        numbers.add(50);

        System.out.println("Numbers:");
        for (int n : numbers) {  // Unboxing
            System.out.println(n);
        }
    }
}
